<p><i><b>Nightfall</b></i> is an American <a href="/wiki/Film_noir" title="Film noir">film noir</a> directed in 1957 by <a href="/wiki/Jacques_Tourneur" title="Jacques Tourneur">Jacques Tourneur</a> and written by <a href="/wiki/Stirling_Silliphant" title="Stirling Silliphant">Stirling Silliphant</a>. It features <a href="/wiki/Aldo_Ray" title="Aldo Ray">Aldo Ray</a>, <a href="/wiki/Brian_Keith" title="Brian Keith">Brian Keith</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Anne_Bancroft" title="Anne Bancroft">Anne Bancroft</a>. 
</p><p>The low-budget film is remembered today for camera work by cinematographer <a href="/wiki/Burnett_Guffey" title="Burnett Guffey">Burnett Guffey</a>. It uses <a href="/wiki/Flashback_(literary_technique)" class="mw-redirect" title="Flashback (literary technique)">flashbacks</a> as a device to tell the story, which was based on a 1947 novel by <a href="/wiki/David_Goodis" title="David Goodis">David Goodis</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
